ndez, Garcia, Jesus, Jorge, Mario, Martinez, Ortiz, Paz, Rodriguez, Rosalina.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Mario</i>, from the Latin name <i>Marius</i>, which is probably of Etruscan origin and possibly related to the name of the Roman god <i>Mars</i>, but was widely adopted from an early date in the Christian era as a male equivalent of the female Christian name   Maria  ."]},{"name":"Margiotta","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Emanuele, Gino, Ignazio, Salvatore, Silvio, Adelmo, Angelo, Anselmo, Antonino, Attilio, Carmine, Elio, Emidio, Mario.","Italian (southern): perhaps a variant of <b>Mariotta</b> (see   Mariotti  ) or a topographic name from medieval Italian <i>mariciotta</i>, a diminutive of <i>maricio</i> ‘salt marsh’ (from Latin <i>maricius</i>)."]},{"name":"Riotto","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Damiano.","Italian:","from a short form of a personal name ending in <i>-otto</i>, such as <i>Mariotto</i> (see   Mariotti  )."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Marguerite Mariotte was born about 1180, in Scotland as the daughter of Gillibrehde. She married MacRath before 1196, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died about 1218, in her hometown, at the age of 40, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1180–about 1218":"umbes 1180–umbes 1218",